<br>
Liberty ships operational protocol means that it begins both the assent and descent stages with essentially clean reactors. The power required for each stage will consume around 10Lbs of uranium, i.e. it will accumulate around 10Lbs of fission waste by the end of each stage.<br>
<br>
ISTM that the worst case scenario would be where an incident resulting in the catastrophic total destruction of the light-bulb containment system on all 7 engines occurring near the end of either stage resulted in the venting of the entire contents of the reactors. <br>
<br>
If this occurred near the end of the boost stage, but before orbit is achieved, the fission products would be dispersed widely through the upper atmosphere. Since they would be dispersed as a gas (more or less) high up in the atmosphere I would imagine that it would take months, or even years for the material to fall to earth. During this time the material would become diluted and dispersed and some of the nastier materials would have time to decay.<br>
<br>
A similar accident on landing would be nastier from a pollution point of view but considerably more localised. If the launch/landing site were suitably remote (mid pacific?) then the overall consequences would be minimal.<br>
<br>
ISTM that Neither of these scenarios would present significant problems for the general population and remember, these are worst-case disasters! Normal Liberty operation produces no external radioactivity at all! If Liberty is designed and built properly it is difficult to see how this level of failure may take place, nevertheless it must be considered. <br>
<br>
On another note, one thing that bothers me about Liberty’s fuel cycle is that it appears to waste a large amount of HEUF6. I imagine that after landing the fuel vaults would be emptied and the “Dirty” fuel would be reprocessed and reused. But the ejection of “Dirty” fuel on achieving orbit would lose large amounts of (very expensive) unused HEUF6. I would prefer the “Dirty” fuel to be stored in a suitable container, which can be put into a known orbit. At some point in the future I would hope that we have orbiting industrial facilities that, amongst other things, could recover and recycle this valuable material.<br>
<br>
Second point, how big can we make Liberty? Would a 10,000-ton payload version be feasible? If so, we are well into Orion territory. I still believe that the advantages of immense lift capability that Orion gives us cannot be beaten but a 10,000 ton Liberty would mean that there may only be a handful of situations where ground launched Orion’s would be advantageous.<br>
<br>
Dusty<br>
